ğŸ“Œ Question

Given two strings needle ğŸª¡ and haystack ğŸªµ, return the index of the first occurrence of needle inside haystack. If not found, return -1.

Examples:
ğŸ‘‰ haystack = "sadbutsad", needle = "sad" â†’ Output = 0
ğŸ‘‰ haystack = "leetcode", needle = "leeto" â†’ Output = -1

Constraints:

1 <= haystack.length, needle.length <= 10^4

All lowercase English letters âœ…

ğŸ’¡ Intuition

Imagine ğŸ“– haystack is a big book and ğŸ” needle is a small word weâ€™re searching.

We need to check each position in haystack and see if needle starts matching from there.

Return the first ğŸ¯ index where it matches.

If not found â†’ return -1 ğŸš«.

ğŸ›  Approach
1ï¸âƒ£ Brute Force (Sliding Window ğŸ”)

Loop through each index of haystack ğŸªµ.

At each index, compare substring of length = needle.length().

If matches â†’ return index.

Time Complexity: O(n * m) (n = haystack length, m = needle length).

2ï¸âƒ£ Built-in Function ğŸ“¦ (Cheat ğŸ˜…)

Just use haystack.indexOf(needle).

Java already has optimized search.

Time Complexity: O(n) average.

3ï¸âƒ£ KMP Algorithm ğŸš€ (Optimal)

Preprocess needle into an LPS (Longest Prefix Suffix) array.

Then scan haystack with needle in O(n + m) time.

Best for large strings ğŸ“.

ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ’» Solutions (Java)
âœ… Brute Force Solution
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String haystack, String needle) {
        int n = haystack.length();
        int m = needle.length();

        for (int i = 0; i <= n - m; i++) {
            if (haystack.substring(i, i + m).equals(needle)) {
                return i; // ğŸ¯ first match
            }
        }
        return -1; // ğŸš« not found
    }
}

âœ… Built-in Solution (Quick Trick ğŸ˜)
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String haystack, String needle) {
        return haystack.indexOf(needle); // ğŸ“¦ directly use Java function
    }
}

âœ… KMP (Optimal ğŸš€)
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String haystack, String needle) {
        int n = haystack.length(), m = needle.length();
        if (m == 0) return 0;

        // Step 1: Build LPS array ğŸ§©
        int[] lps = new int[m];
        for (int i = 1, len = 0; i < m; ) {
            if (needle.charAt(i) == needle.charAt(len)) {
                lps[i++] = ++len;
            } else if (len > 0) {
                len = lps[len - 1];
            } else {
                lps[i++] = 0;
            }
        }

        // Step 2: Match haystack vs needle ğŸ”
        for (int i = 0, j = 0; i < n; ) {
            if (haystack.charAt(i) == needle.charAt(j)) {
                i++; j++;
                if (j == m) return i - j; // ğŸ¯ found
            } else if (j > 0) {
                j = lps[j - 1];
            } else {
                i++;
            }
        }
        return -1; // ğŸš« not found
    }
}

ğŸ¯ Final Takeaways

For interviews â†’ Explain Brute Force â Built-in â KMP.

For real coding â†’ haystack.indexOf(needle) is enough ğŸ˜‰.

KMP is important conceptually (pattern searching).